## Implementation Plan: Custom Theme System for T3 Code

### Architecture Overview

The theme system has two layers:

1. **Data layer** (`packages/shared/src/themes.ts`) -- Pure theme definitions, lookup functions, no React or DOM dependencies. Follows the same export pattern as `model.ts`.

2. **Application layer** (`apps/web/src/hooks/useTheme.ts` + CSS) -- Evolves the existing `useTheme` hook to support named themes while preserving the `useSyncExternalStore` pattern, `.dark` class toggling, and backward compatibility with all existing consumers.

### Key Design Decisions

**Decision 1: Evolve `useTheme`, do not create a parallel system.**

The existing `useTheme` hook is consumed in 5 files (`_chat.settings.tsx`, `DiffWorkerPoolProvider.tsx`, `DiffPanel.tsx`, `ChatMarkdown.tsx`, `ChatView.tsx`). All consumers access `resolvedTheme` (typed as `"light" | "dark"`) for diff theme resolution and icon theming. Creating a separate hook would mean either duplicating concerns or requiring all consumers to adopt a new import. Instead, the existing hook will be extended to also carry the active theme ID, and `resolvedTheme` will continue to work exactly as before.

**Decision 2: Theme colors map onto existing CSS custom properties AND add new ones.**

The existing CSS variable system (`--background`, `--foreground`, `--primary`, `--accent`, `--border`, etc.) is referenced throughout all Tailwind classes and hardcoded CSS. The theme definitions must set these existing properties so that `bg-background`, `text-foreground`, etc. continue to work. Additional theme-specific properties (`--sidebar-*`, `--editor-*`, `--terminal-*`, `--statusbar-*`) are added alongside.

**Decision 3: "t3-dark" and "t3-light" replicate current color values; "t3-midnight" introduces a third palette.**

When "t3-dark" is active, the CSS variables produce the same values as the current `@variant dark` block. When "t3-light" is active, they match the current `:root` values. This means existing users see zero visual change. The `.dark` class is toggled for any theme where `isDark: true`, keeping Tailwind's dark variant and all existing `.dark ::-webkit-scrollbar-thumb` CSS selectors working.

**Decision 4: CSS custom properties are applied via `document.documentElement.style.setProperty`, not by injecting `<style>` tags.**

This is the simplest approach that requires no build tool changes. Each theme carries a `cssProperties` record mapping CSS variable names to values. When a theme is applied, these are set on `document.documentElement.style`. When switching away, the old properties are cleared. The static CSS in `index.css` serves as fallback/defaults only.

**Decision 5: Storage uses a separate localStorage key (`t3code:color-theme`) and the old key (`t3code:theme`) is preserved for migration.**

The old key stores `"light" | "dark" | "system"`. The new key stores a theme ID string like `"t3-dark"`. On first load, if the new key is absent but the old key is present, the system migrates: `"dark"` becomes `"t3-dark"`, `"light"` becomes `"t3-light"`, `"system"` becomes `null` (auto-detect). After migration, both keys are kept in sync so that any code path reading the old key still gets a coherent `"light" | "dark" | "system"` value.

---

### File-by-File Implementation

#### 1. NEW: `packages/shared/src/themes.ts`

This module defines theme data. It uses the same coding conventions as `model.ts`: pure functions, `as const satisfies`, no classes, no external dependencies beyond TypeScript types.

**Types to define:**

```typescript
export type ThemeId = string & { readonly __brand: unique symbol };

export interface ThemeColorSet {
  readonly background: string;
  readonly foreground: string;
  readonly card: string;
  readonly cardForeground: string;
  readonly popover: string;
  readonly popoverForeground: string;
  readonly primary: string;
  readonly primaryForeground: string;
  readonly secondary: string;
  readonly secondaryForeground: string;
  readonly muted: string;
  readonly mutedForeground: string;
  readonly accent: string;
  readonly accentForeground: string;
  readonly destructive: string;
  readonly destructiveForeground: string;
  readonly border: string;
  readonly input: string;
  readonly ring: string;
  // Status colors
  readonly info: string;
  readonly infoForeground: string;
  readonly success: string;
  readonly successForeground: string;
  readonly warning: string;
  readonly warningForeground: string;
  // Extended surface colors
  readonly sidebar: string;
  readonly sidebarForeground: string;
  readonly editor: string;
  readonly editorForeground: string;
  readonly terminal: string;
  readonly terminalForeground: string;
  readonly statusBar: string;
  readonly statusBarForeground: string;
}

export interface ThemeDefinition {
  readonly id: ThemeId;
  readonly name: string;
  readonly isDark: boolean;
  readonly colors: ThemeColorSet;
  readonly fontFamily?: string;
  readonly fontSize?: number;
  readonly radius?: string;
}
```

**Built-in themes** defined as `const BUILTIN_THEMES = [...] as const satisfies readonly ThemeDefinition[]`:

- **"t3-dark"**: `isDark: true`. Colors exactly match the current `@variant dark` block values from `index.css` lines 94-120. The extended surfaces (`sidebar`, `editor`, `terminal`, `statusBar`) derive from the dark card/background colors. Name: "T3 Dark".
- **"t3-light"**: `isDark: false`. Colors exactly match the current `:root` block values from `index.css` lines 64-91. Extended surfaces derive from the light card/background colors. Name: "T3 Light".
- **"t3-midnight"**: `isDark: true`. A deeper, more saturated dark theme. Background uses a near-black `oklch(0.13 0.01 260)`, accent uses a brighter blue-violet, and the sidebar/statusBar get a subtly different tone. Name: "T3 Midnight".

**Exported functions** (following `model.ts` pattern):

```typescript
export function listThemes(): readonly ThemeDefinition[]
export function getTheme(id: string): ThemeDefinition | null
export function getDefaultThemeId(): ThemeId  // returns "t3-dark"
```

A helper function maps `ThemeColorSet` fields to CSS custom property names:

```typescript
export function themeToCssProperties(theme: ThemeDefinition): Record<string, string>
```

This function returns a flat record like `{ "--background": "...", "--foreground": "...", "--sidebar": "...", ... }`. The mapping from camelCase `ThemeColorSet` keys to CSS variable names is explicit (e.g., `cardForeground` -> `--card-foreground`). The extended surfaces introduce new CSS variables (`--sidebar`, `--sidebar-foreground`, etc.).

#### 2. MODIFY: `packages/shared/package.json`

Add a new subpath export entry:

```json
"./themes": {
  "types": "./src/themes.ts",
  "import": "./src/themes.ts"
}
```

This follows the existing pattern for `./model`, `./git`, etc.

#### 3. NEW: `packages/shared/src/themes.test.ts`

Unit tests following the `model.test.ts` pattern:

- `listThemes()` returns exactly 3 themes
- `getTheme("t3-dark")` returns the correct theme with `isDark: true`
- `getTheme("t3-light")` returns the correct theme with `isDark: false`
- `getTheme("t3-midnight")` returns the correct theme with `isDark: true`
- `getTheme("nonexistent")` returns `null`
- `getDefaultThemeId()` returns `"t3-dark"`
- `themeToCssProperties()` returns correct CSS variable names and values
- Every theme's `ThemeColorSet` has all required keys

#### 4. MODIFY: `apps/web/src/hooks/useTheme.ts`

This is the most critical change. The current module-level state pattern (`useSyncExternalStore` + external listeners + `localStorage`) is preserved but extended.

**New storage key:** `const THEME_STORAGE_KEY = "t3code:color-theme"` (alongside existing `STORAGE_KEY = "t3code:theme"`).

**New imports:**

```typescript
import { getTheme, getDefaultThemeId, listThemes, themeToCssProperties, type ThemeId, type ThemeDefinition } from "@t3tools/shared/themes";
```

**Updated snapshot type:**

```typescript
type ThemeSnapshot = {
  theme: Theme;             // "light" | "dark" | "system" -- preserved for backward compat
  systemDark: boolean;
  themeId: ThemeId;          // e.g. "t3-dark", "t3-light", "t3-midnight"
  themeDefinition: ThemeDefinition;
};
```

**Core logic changes:**

`getStoredThemeId()`: Reads `THEME_STORAGE_KEY` from localStorage, validates via `getTheme()`, falls back to inferring from the old `STORAGE_KEY` value:
- If old key is `"dark"` or `"system"` (and system is dark) -> `"t3-dark"`
- If old key is `"light"` or `"system"` (and system is light) -> `"t3-light"`
- Default: `getDefaultThemeId()`

`applyTheme()` is extended: After toggling `.dark` based on `themeDefinition.isDark`, it calls `applyThemeCssProperties(themeDefinition)` which iterates `themeToCssProperties(themeDefinition)` and calls `document.documentElement.style.setProperty(name, value)` for each entry. A reference to the previously applied property names is stored at module level so they can be cleared when switching themes (via `document.documentElement.style.removeProperty(name)`).

`setTheme()` is preserved with the same signature for backward compatibility but internally also persists the theme ID. A new `setThemeById(themeId: ThemeId)` function is added that determines the correct `Theme` value ("light" or "dark") from the theme definition and calls through.

**Updated hook return type:**

```typescript
return {
  theme,           // "light" | "dark" | "system" -- same as before
  setTheme,        // (next: Theme) => void -- same signature, still works
  resolvedTheme,   // "light" | "dark" -- same as before
  themeId,         // ThemeId -- new
  themeDefinition, // ThemeDefinition -- new
  setThemeById,    // (id: ThemeId) => void -- new
  availableThemes, // readonly ThemeDefinition[] -- new (calls listThemes())
} as const;
```

**Backward compatibility:** Every existing consumer destructures `{ resolvedTheme }` or `{ theme, setTheme, resolvedTheme }`. These all continue to work unchanged. The new properties are additive.

**Module-load apply:** The line `applyTheme(getStored())` at module level is updated to also read and apply the full theme definition, so there is no flash of unstyled content.

**Cross-tab sync:** The `storage` event handler already re-reads from localStorage and calls `applyTheme`. It is updated to also handle `THEME_STORAGE_KEY` changes.

#### 5. MODIFY: `apps/web/src/index.css`

Minimal changes needed:

**Add new CSS custom properties for extended surfaces** in both `:root` and `@variant dark` blocks, with sensible defaults that match the current look:

```css
:root {
  /* ... existing vars ... */
  --sidebar: var(--card);
  --sidebar-foreground: var(--card-foreground);
  --editor: var(--background);
  --editor-foreground: var(--foreground);
  --terminal: var(--background);
  --terminal-foreground: var(--foreground);
  --statusbar: var(--card);
  --statusbar-foreground: var(--card-foreground);
}
```

And the corresponding `@variant dark` block gets the same set of new variables pointing to the dark defaults. These act as fallbacks; the JS theme applicator will override them with theme-specific values at runtime.

**Add new `--color-*` mappings** in the `@theme inline` block for the new variables, so Tailwind utility classes like `bg-sidebar`, `text-sidebar-foreground` work:

```css
@theme inline {
  /* ... existing ... */
  --color-sidebar: var(--sidebar);
  --color-sidebar-foreground: var(--sidebar-foreground);
  --color-editor: var(--editor);
  --color-editor-foreground: var(--editor-foreground);
  --color-terminal: var(--terminal);
  --color-terminal-foreground: var(--terminal-foreground);
  --color-statusbar: var(--statusbar);
  --color-statusbar-foreground: var(--statusbar-foreground);
}
```

#### 6. MODIFY: `apps/web/src/routes/_chat.settings.tsx`

The "Appearance" section is redesigned to replace the simple light/dark/system radio group with a theme selector that includes preview swatches.

**Changes to the imports:**

```typescript
import { useTheme } from "../hooks/useTheme";
// No longer need THEME_OPTIONS const for the basic 3 options
```

**New `THEME_OPTIONS` replacement:** Remove the hardcoded `THEME_OPTIONS` array. Instead, use `availableThemes` from the hook.

**New Appearance section structure:**

The section still lives in the same `<section className="rounded-2xl ...">` card. The content changes to:

1. A grid of theme cards (one per available theme). Each card shows:
   - The theme name
   - A preview swatch -- a small rectangle with 4-5 color circles showing the theme's background, foreground, primary, accent, and sidebar colors
   - A "Selected" badge when active

2. Below the grid, a "System preference" toggle (a Switch component) that, when enabled, auto-selects `t3-light` or `t3-dark` based on `prefers-color-scheme`. When disabled, the explicit theme selection is honored.

**Implementation detail for the theme card/swatch:**

```tsx
function ThemePreviewCard({ theme, isSelected, onSelect }: {
  theme: ThemeDefinition;
  isSelected: boolean;
  onSelect: () => void;
}) {
  // Renders a button with:
  // - A row of small colored circles for: background, primary, accent, sidebar, foreground
  // - Theme name text
  // - Selected badge if active
  // Uses the same styling conventions as the existing THEME_OPTIONS buttons
}
```

The `onClick` handler calls `setThemeById(theme.id)`.

**System preference toggle:** A new piece of state is needed to track whether the user wants system-based theme selection. This can be stored as a special value in localStorage (e.g., the theme ID stored as `"system"`) or as a boolean alongside the theme ID. When system mode is active and the OS preference changes, the hook auto-switches between `t3-light` and `t3-dark`.

The settings page extracts from the hook:

```typescript
const { themeId, setThemeById, availableThemes, resolvedTheme, theme } = useTheme();
```

The "Active theme" line at the bottom becomes: `Active theme: T3 Dark (dark)` showing both the theme name and the resolved light/dark mode.

#### 7. MODIFY: `apps/web/src/components/DiffWorkerPoolProvider.tsx`

No changes required. It already destructures `{ resolvedTheme }` from `useTheme()`, and `resolvedTheme` is still `"light" | "dark"`. The hook extension is backward-compatible.

#### 8. MODIFY: `apps/web/src/components/DiffPanel.tsx`

No changes required. Same reasoning as above.

#### 9. MODIFY: `apps/web/src/components/ChatMarkdown.tsx`

No changes required. Same reasoning.

#### 10. MODIFY: `apps/web/src/components/ChatView.tsx`

No changes required. Same reasoning. All `resolvedTheme` usage continues to work.

#### 11. MODIFY: `apps/web/src/routes/_chat.tsx`

Optionally, the sidebar `<Sidebar>` component can be updated to use `bg-sidebar` instead of `bg-card` to take advantage of the new theme surface colors:

```tsx
<Sidebar
  side="left"
  collapsible="offcanvas"
  className="border-r border-border bg-sidebar text-sidebar-foreground"
>
```

This is a small refinement, not a requirement.

